  "prompt": "Suppose that X has a discrete uniform distribution on the integers 0 through 9. How can I determine the mean, variance, and standard deviation of the random variable Y = 5X?",
  "response": "To find the mean, variance, and standard deviation of the random variable \\( Y = 5X \\), where \\( X \\) has a discrete uniform distribution on the integers from 0 to 9, we can follow these steps:\n\n### Step 1: Calculate the Mean of \\( X \\)\n\nFor a discrete uniform distribution \\( X \\) that takes on values \\( 0, 1, 2, \\ldots, n-1 \\) (where \\( n = 10 \\) in this case), the mean \\( \\mu_X \\) is given by:\n\n\\[\n\\mu_X = \\frac{(0 + 1 + 2 + \\ldots + 9)}{10} = \\frac{9 \\cdot (9 + 1)/2}{10} = \\frac{45}{10} = 4.5\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Calculate the Variance of \\( X \\)\n\nThe variance \\( \\sigma_X^2 \\) of a discrete uniform distribution can be calculated using:\n\n\\[\n\\sigma_X^2 = \\frac{(n^2 - 1)}{12}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\( n \\) is the number of values. Here \\( n = 10 \\), so:\n\n\\[\n\\sigma_X^2 = \\frac{(10^2 - 1)}{12} = \\frac{99}{12} = 8.25\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Calculate the Mean of \\( Y \\)\n\nSince \\( Y = 5X \\), we can find the mean of \\( Y \\) using the property of expectations:\n\n\\[\n\\mu_Y = E[Y] = E[5X] = 5E[X] = 5\\mu_X = 5 \\cdot 4.5 = 22.5\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculate the Variance of \\( Y \\)\n\nThe variance of \\( Y \\) can be found using the property of variances:\n\n\\[\n\\sigma_Y^2 = Var[Y] = Var[5X] = 5^2 Var[X] = 25 \\sigma_X^2\n\\]\n\nCalculating this gives:\n\n\\[\n\\sigma_Y^2 = 25 \\cdot 8.25 = 206.25\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Calculate the Standard Deviation of \\( Y \\)\n\nThe standard deviation is the square root of the variance:\n\n\\[\n\\sigma_Y = \\sqrt{\\sigma_Y^2} = \\sqrt{206.25} = 14.37 \\quad (\\text{approx.})\n\\]\n\n### Summary of Results\n\n- Mean of \\( Y \\): \\( \\mu_Y = 22.5 \\)\n- Variance of \\( Y \\): \\( \\sigma_Y^2 = 206.25 \\)\n- Standard Deviation of \\( Y \\): \\( \\sigma_Y \\approx 14.37 \\)\n\nThese results summarize the mean, variance, and standard deviation of the random variable \\( Y = 5X \\).",
